  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Source Term.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathbf{J}\\times\\mathbf{B}\n+\n\\rho_e\\mathbf{E}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Electromagnetic Torque Integral.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boldsymbol{\\tau}_{\\mathrm{em}}\n=\n\\int_V\n\\mathbf{r}\\times\n\\left(\n\\mathbf{J}\\times\\mathbf{B}\n+\n\\rho_e\\mathbf{E}\n\\right)\n\\,\\mathrm{d}V .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Angular Momentum Generation Law.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\frac{\\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{L}}{\\mathrm{d}t}\n=\n\\boldsymbol{\\tau}_{\\mathrm{em}} .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nThe local electromagnetic force density is:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathbf{f}_{\\mathrm{em}}\n=\n\\mathbf{J}\\times\\mathbf{B}\n+\n\\rho_e\\mathbf{E}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nTorque density is position crossed with force density:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathbf{r}\\times\\mathbf{f}_{\\mathrm{em}}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nIntegrating over a source region $V$ gives:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boldsymbol{\\tau}_{\\mathrm{em}}\n=\n\\int_V\n\\mathbf{r}\\times\n\\left(\n\\mathbf{J}\\times\\mathbf{B}\n+\n\\rho_e\\mathbf{E}\n\\right)\n\\,\\mathrm{d}V .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe angular momentum generation law is therefore:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\frac{\\mathrm{d}\\mathbf{L}}{\\mathrm{d}t}\n=\n\\boldsymbol{\\tau}_{\\mathrm{em}} .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nAngular momentum is modeled as continuously generated by local electromagnetic source terms rather than assumed as a primordial input.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
